    "remark": "Insight: a companion matrix wears its characteristic polynomial on its sleeve, and irreducibility guarantees it is non-derogatory, so every polynomial relation it satisfies is forced by $p$ alone. Two ostensibly different computations — Cayley–Hamilton's algebraic inversion $A^{-1}=A^3-I$ and the symmetric-function reciprocity $\\sum 1/\\lambda_i=e_3/e_4$ — must agree, and they pin the same value $-1$. The sole danger is the reciprocity sign: $\\sum 1/\\lambda_i$ is $e_{n-1}/e_n$, and translating coefficients to elementary symmetric functions carries alternating signs ($e_3=-c_1$, $e_4=+c_0$). Because the degree is even, $e_4=\\det A=p(0)=-1$ is negative, and the temptingly clean $+1$ is exactly wrong."
