    "statement": "Fix nonzero column vectors $u,v\\in\\mathbb R^{n}$ and set $s = v^{\\to p}u$ and $A = I + uv^{\\to p}$. Assuming $s\\neq -1$ and $s\\neq 0$, find $\\det A$, all eigenvalues of $A$ with multiplicities, and a closed form for $A^{m}$ ($m\\ge 1$).",
    "answer": "$\\det A = 1+s.\\quad \\text{Eigenvalues: } 1 \\ (\\text{mult } n-1),\\ 1+s \\ (\\text{mult } 1).\\quad A^{m} = I + \\dfrac{(1+s)^{m}-1}{s}\\,uv^{\\to p}.$",
    "trap": "Trying to diagonalise the dense matrix $uv^{\\to p}$ entry-by-entry, or expanding an $n\\times n$ determinant directly. The key is that $uv^{\\to p}$ has **rank one**: as an operator it has the single eigenvalue $s=v^{\\to p}u=\\operatorname{tr}(uv^{\\to p})$ (eigenvector $u$) and $0$ on the $(n-1)$-dimensional space $v^{\\perp}$. Forgetting the engine identity $(uv^{\\to p})^2=(v^{\\to p}u)\\,uv^{\\to p}=s\\,uv^{\\to p}$ — i.e. the rank-one matrix reproduces itself (up to the scalar $s$) under squaring — makes $A^m$ look intractable. A second trap is assuming $s\\ne0$ is cosmetic: it is exactly the condition that makes the closed form $\\frac{(1+s)^m-1}{s}$ valid and guarantees $u\\notin v^{\\perp}$, so the two eigenspaces actually span $\\mathbb R^n$.",
    "solutions": [
      {
        "name": "Rank-one self-reproduction",
        "steps": [
          "Let $R=uv^{\\to p}$. Then $R^2=u(v^{\\to p}u)v^{\\to p}=sR$, so $R$ annihilates the polynomial $t^2-st=t(t-s)$: its only eigenvalues are $s$ (eigenvector $u$, since $Ru=su$) and $0$ (the $(n-1)$-dimensional space $v^{\\perp}=\\{x:v^{\\to p}x=0\\}$, since $Rx=u(v^{\\to p}x)=0$ there).",
          "Hence $A=I+R$ has eigenvalues $1+s$ (once) and $1$ ($n-1$ times). Its characteristic polynomial is $(x-1)^{n-1}\\bigl(x-(1+s)\\bigr)$, so $\\det A=(1+s)\\cdot1^{\\,n-1}=1+s$ (the matrix-determinant lemma).",
          "For powers, write $A^m=I+c_mR$ and multiply: $A^{m+1}=A^m(I+R)=I+c_mR+R+c_mR^2=I+(c_m+1+c_ms)R$, using $R^2=sR$. This gives $c_{m+1}=(1+s)c_m+1$ with $c_1=1$.",
          "Solving the affine linear recurrence (fixed point $c^{*}=-1/s$ since $s\\ne0$): $c_m=\\dfrac{(1+s)^m-1}{s}$, so $A^m=I+\\dfrac{(1+s)^m-1}{s}\\,uv^{\\to p}$."
        ]
      },
      {
        "name": "Diagonalise on two invariant pieces",
        "steps": [
          "On $v^{\\perp}=\\{x:v^{\\to p}x=0\\}$ (dimension $n-1$), $Ax=x+u(v^{\\to p}x)=x$, so $A$ acts as the identity and $A^mx=x$.",
          "On the line $\\mathbb R u$, $Au=u+u(v^{\\to p}u)=(1+s)u$, so $A^mu=(1+s)^mu$. Because $s=v^{\\to p}u\\ne0$, $u\\notin v^{\\perp}$, so $\\mathbb R u\\oplus v^{\\perp}=\\mathbb R^n$ and these two invariant subspaces span everything.",
          "Decompose any $x=x_0+\\alpha u$ with $x_0\\in v^{\\perp}$. Matching $A^m$ on both pieces, the operator $A^m$ fixes $v^{\\perp}$ and scales $u$ by $(1+s)^m$; the unique such operator of the form $I+cR$ has $c=\\dfrac{(1+s)^m-1}{s}$ (checking on $u$: $1+cs=(1+s)^m$). Hence $A^m=I+\\dfrac{(1+s)^m-1}{s}uv^{\\to p}$.",
          "Reading off the spectrum: $\\det A=1+s$, eigenvalues $1$ (mult $n-1$) and $1+s$ (once)."
        ]
      },
      {
        "name": "Cayley–Hamilton on the $2\\times2$ trace block",
        "steps": [
          "Restrict attention to $W=\\operatorname{span}\\{u\\}$ and note $A=I+R$ with $R^2=sR$. Thus $R$ satisfies its minimal polynomial $\\mu_R(t)=t(t-s)$ (both factors needed since $R\\ne0$ and $R\\ne sI$ for $n\\ge2$), so $A=I+R$ satisfies $\\mu_A(x)=(x-1)\\bigl(x-(1+s)\\bigr)$.",
          "From $\\mu_A$, every power $A^m$ is a linear combination $A^m=\\alpha_m I+\\beta_m A$; equivalently $A^m=I+c_mR$. Evaluating the scalar identity $x^m\\equiv \\text{(value)}$ at the two eigenvalues $x=1$ and $x=1+s$ pins down $c_m$: at $x=1$, $1=1$ (automatic); at $x=1+s$, $(1+s)^m=1+c_ms$, giving $c_m=\\dfrac{(1+s)^m-1}{s}$.",
          "Therefore $A^m=I+\\dfrac{(1+s)^m-1}{s}\\,uv^{\\to p}$.",
          "Taking $m=1$ recovers $A$; the determinant is the product of eigenvalues $1^{\\,n-1}(1+s)=1+s$, with eigenvalues $1$ (mult $n-1$) and $1+s$ (once)."
        ]
      }
    ],
    "remark": "**Insight.** Every rank-one update $I+uv^{\\to p}$ is governed by a single scalar $s=v^{\\to p}u$: it perturbs exactly one eigenvalue ($1\\mapsto1+s$) and leaves an $(n-1)$-dimensional fixed space $v^{\\perp}$. The identity $(uv^{\\to p})^2=s\\,uv^{\\to p}$ is the engine behind the matrix-determinant lemma ($\\det(I+uv^{\\to p})=1+v^{\\to p}u$), the Sherman–Morrison inverse ($A^{-1}=I-\\frac{1}{1+s}uv^{\\to p}$, valid since $s\\ne-1$), and this whole family of closed forms — indeed the power formula $A^m=I+\\frac{(1+s)^m-1}{s}uv^{\\to p}$ extends to $m=-1$ and recovers Sherman–Morrison exactly."
