          "Since $L=L^{\\mathsf T}$, the column space equals the row space, and a symmetric system $Lx=b$ is solvable iff $b\\perp\\ker L^{\\mathsf T}=\\ker L=\\operatorname{span}(\\mathbf 1)$, i.e. iff $\\mathbf 1^{\\mathsf T}b=\\sum_i b_i=0$. When this holds, the solution set is a coset of $\\ker L$, so its dimension is $\\dim\\ker L=1$.",
          "Finally $L$ is symmetric positive-semidefinite, hence diagonalizable with eigenvalues $\\ge 0$; $L^{k}$ has the same eigenvectors with eigenvalues $\\lambda^{k}$, which vanish exactly where $\\lambda=0$. So $\\ker(L^{k})=\\ker L$ and $\\operatorname{rank}(L^{k})=n-1$ for all $k\\ge1$. $\\boxed{\\operatorname{rank}L=n-1,\\ \\text{solvable}\\iff\\mathbf 1^{\\mathsf T}b=0,\\ \\dim=1,\\ \\operatorname{rank}L^{k}=n-1}$"
