    "answer": "\\operatorname{rank}(AB) takes exactly the integers k with \\max(0,\\,r+s-n)\\le k\\le \\min(r,s), and every such k is attained.",
    "trap": "The reflexive answer is \"$\\operatorname{rank}(AB)\\le\\min(r,s)$, so the possible values are $0,1,\\dots,\\min(r,s)$\" — forgetting that the product cannot drop *too far*. **Sylvester's inequality forces a floor** $\\operatorname{rank}(AB)\\ge r+s-n$, which is positive once $r+s>n$. Omitting this lower obstruction (assuming any small rank, even $0$, is always reachable) is the classic error; e.g. two invertible $n\\times n$ matrices have $r=s=n$ and the product is forced to rank $n$, not $0$.",
