    "trap": "The fatal reflex is to use only $\\operatorname{tr} C = \\operatorname{tr}(AB-BA)=0$ and conclude that the eigenvalues merely sum to zero. A strong student then reasons: \"a trace-zero matrix can perfectly well have spectrum like $\\{\\lambda,-\\lambda,0,\\dots\\}$, so $C$ need not be nilpotent, and $\\det(I_n+tC)$ should depend on those hidden $\\pm\\lambda$.\" This is exactly right for a GENERAL commutator (rank $\\ge 2$): there genuine nonzero eigenvalues do occur, since every trace-zero matrix is a commutator. The trap is forgetting that the rank-$1$ hypothesis is doing heavy lifting. A rank-$\\le 1$ matrix has AT MOST ONE nonzero eigenvalue, and that lone eigenvalue must equal $\\operatorname{tr} C$. So 'eigenvalues sum to zero' degenerates to 'the single eigenvalue IS zero' — the rank cap and the trace law collide and annihilate the spectrum. The student who keeps a phantom $\\pm\\lambda$ will predict $\\det(I_n+tC)=1-\\lambda^2 t^2\\neq 1$ and a nonzero $\\operatorname{tr}(C^{2026})$, both wrong. The second, subtler trap: even knowing all eigenvalues are $0$, one might fear $C$ is only nilpotent of high index, so $\\operatorname{tr}(C^{2026})$ needs the index; in fact rank $1$ forces $C^2=0$ outright, killing every power at once.",
    "solutions": [
      {
        "name": "Rank cap meets the trace law",
        "steps": [
          "Since $\\operatorname{rank} C = 1$, the image of $C$ is a line $\\mathbb{C}u$, so we may write $C=u\\,v^{\\to p}$ for nonzero column vectors $u,v\\in\\mathbb{C}^n$ (every rank-one matrix is such an outer product). Then $\\operatorname{tr} C=\\operatorname{tr}(u v^{\\to p})=v^{\\to p}u$.",
          "Because $C$ is a commutator, $\\operatorname{tr} C=\\operatorname{tr}(AB)-\\operatorname{tr}(BA)=0$ by the cyclic law $\\operatorname{tr}(XY)=\\operatorname{tr}(YX)$. Hence $v^{\\to p}u=0$.",
          "A rank-one matrix has characteristic polynomial $t^{\\,n-1}\\bigl(t-\\operatorname{tr} C\\bigr)$: its only possible nonzero eigenvalue is $\\operatorname{tr} C$, on the eigenvector $u$ (indeed $Cu=u(v^{\\to p}u)=(\\operatorname{tr} C)\\,u$), while the $(n-1)$-dimensional kernel of $v^{\\to p}$ gives eigenvalue $0$. With $\\operatorname{tr} C=0$ this collapses to $t^{\\,n}$, so EVERY eigenvalue of $C$ is $0$ and $C$ is nilpotent. This answers (a).",
          "Moreover $C^2=u\\,(v^{\\to p}u)\\,v^{\\to p}=(\\operatorname{tr} C)\\,C=0$, so $C^{\\,k}=0$ for all $k\\ge 2$; in particular $\\operatorname{tr}(C^{2026})=0$. And by the matrix determinant lemma $\\det(I_n+t\\,u v^{\\to p})=1+t\\,v^{\\to p}u=1$ for all $t$, which is (b). Therefore $\\det(I_n+2026\\,C)+\\operatorname{tr}(C^{2026})=1+0=\\boxed{1}$."
        ]
      },
      {
        "name": "Characteristic polynomial via Newton / power sums",
        "steps": [
          "Let $\\lambda_1,\\dots,\\lambda_n$ be the eigenvalues of $C$. The power sums are $p_k=\\sum_i\\lambda_i^{\\,k}=\\operatorname{tr}(C^{\\,k})$. Since $\\operatorname{rank} C=1$, we have $\\operatorname{rank}(C^{\\,k})\\le 1$ and indeed $C^{\\,k}=(\\operatorname{tr} C)^{\\,k-1}C$ (from $C=uv^{\\to p}$, $C^{\\,k}=(v^{\\to p}u)^{\\,k-1}C$). Thus $p_k=(\\operatorname{tr} C)^{\\,k}$ for all $k\\ge 1$.",
          "The commutator identity forces $p_1=\\operatorname{tr} C=0$, hence $p_k=0^{\\,k}=0$ for every $k\\ge 1$: ALL power sums of $C$ vanish.",
          "Newton's identities express the elementary symmetric functions $e_k$ of the $\\lambda_i$ through the $p_k$; with $p_1=p_2=\\cdots=0$ they yield $e_1=e_2=\\cdots=e_n=0$. So the characteristic polynomial is $t^{\\,n}$, all eigenvalues are $0$ (part (a)), and $\\det(I_n+tC)=\\prod_i(1+t\\lambda_i)=1$ identically (part (b)).",
          "Finally $\\operatorname{tr}(C^{2026})=p_{2026}=0$ and $\\det(I_n+2026\\,C)=1$, so the requested quantity is $1+0=\\boxed{1}$. (Contrast: drop the rank hypothesis and only $p_1=0$ survives; the higher $p_k$ are then free, the spectrum can be nonzero, and the determinant is genuinely a nonconstant polynomial in $t$.)"
        ]
      },
      {
        "name": "Cayley-Hamilton shortcut on the rank-one image",
        "steps": [
          "Restrict attention to the one-dimensional image $W=\\operatorname{im}C$. Since $\\operatorname{rank}C=1$, $C$ maps $\\mathbb{C}^n$ onto $W$ and acts on $W$ as multiplication by a single scalar $\\mu$ (a linear self-map of a line is a scalar). For $w\\in W$, $Cw=\\mu w$, so the trace of $C$ — computed in any basis adapted to $W\\oplus\\ker C$ — equals $\\mu$ (the kernel contributes $0$'s on the diagonal). Hence $\\mu=\\operatorname{tr}C$.",
          "The commutator structure gives $\\operatorname{tr}C=0$, so $\\mu=0$: $C$ is the zero map on its own image. Consequently $C^2=0$ (apply $C$, land in $W$, then $C$ kills $W$), confirming $C$ is nilpotent of index $\\le 2$ and every eigenvalue is $0$ — part (a). Because the index is $\\le 2$, $C^{2026}=0$ and $\\operatorname{tr}(C^{2026})=0$.",
          "For the determinant, note $(I_n+tC)$ has the single inverse $I_n-tC$ since $(I_n+tC)(I_n-tC)=I_n-t^2C^2=I_n$. A matrix with a polynomial inverse of determinant-product $\\det(I_n+tC)\\det(I_n-tC)=\\det(I_n-t^2C^2)=\\det I_n=1$, together with $\\det(I_n+tC)=\\det(I_n-tC)$ (replace $t\\to-t$ leaves the nilpotent determinant unchanged because all eigenvalues are $0$, so each factor is $1$), pins $\\det(I_n+tC)=1$ — part (b).",
          "Therefore $\\det(I_n+2026\\,C)+\\operatorname{tr}(C^{2026})=1+0=\\boxed{1}$."
        ]
      }
    ],
    "remark": "Insight: the humble identity $\\operatorname{tr}(AB)=\\operatorname{tr}(BA)$ is being used as a rank-obstruction, not merely a bookkeeping trick. For a GENERAL matrix, knowing only $\\operatorname{tr}=0$ tells you the eigenvalues sum to zero and nothing more — a trace-zero matrix can be wildly non-nilpotent (e.g. $\\operatorname{diag}(5,-5,0)$), and every trace-zero matrix is in fact a commutator $AB-BA$. The whole game changes the instant you bound the rank: a rank-$1$ matrix has at most one nonzero eigenvalue, that eigenvalue is forced to be the trace, and trace $=0$ then leaves the spectrum with nowhere to hide — it must be $\\{0,\\dots,0\\}$, so $C$ is nilpotent and even $C^2=0$. This is the cleanest instance of a recurring top-rank theme: a single scalar invariant (the trace) plus a single dimension count (the rank) can together force an entire spectrum to collapse, something no amount of brute-force eigenvalue chasing reveals. The same two-line argument shows $AB-BA=I$ is impossible (trace $0\\neq n$) and that any rank-$1$ perturbation of a scalar that must have trace $0$ is automatically nilpotent; conversely it warns that 'commutator $\\Rightarrow$ nilpotent' is FALSE without the rank cap."
