    "statement": "Let $n\\ge 1$ and let $A\\in M_n(\\mathbb{C})$ be an involution, i.e. $A^2=I_n$. Let $m_{+}=\\dim\\ker(A-I_n)$ and $m_{-}=\\dim\\ker(A+I_n)$ denote the dimensions of the $+1$ and $-1$ eigenspaces.\\par (a) Prove that every eigenvalue of $A$ lies in $\\{+1,-1\\}$, that $A$ is diagonalizable, and that\n\\[\nm_{+}=\\frac{n+\\operatorname{tr}A}{2},\\qquad m_{-}=\\frac{n-\\operatorname{tr}A}{2}.\n\\]\nDeduce that $\\operatorname{tr}A$ and $n$ have the same parity, and that $\\operatorname{tr}A\\in\\{-n,-n+2,\\dots,n-2,n\\}$.\n\\par (b) A colleague asserts that some $2024\\times 2024$ involution has $\\operatorname{tr}A=1233$. Decide, with proof, whether such a matrix exists.\n\\par (c) Now suppose $n=2024$ and $\\operatorname{tr}A=1234$. Compute $m_{+}=\\dim\\ker(A-I_n)$.",
