    "statement": "Let $P,Q\\in M_n(\\mathbb{R})$ be orthogonal projections, i.e. $P=P^{\\to p}=P^{2}$ and $Q=Q^{\\to p}=Q^{2}$, projecting onto subspaces $\\mathcal{U}=\\operatorname{im}P$ and $\\mathcal{V}=\\operatorname{im}Q$ of dimensions $p=\\operatorname{rank}P$ and $q=\\operatorname{rank}Q$. The product $PQ$ is in general not symmetric and not a projection.\\par (a) Prove that for every integer $k\\ge 1$ the number $\\operatorname{tr}\\bigl((PQ)^{k}\\bigr)$ is real and satisfies $\\operatorname{tr}\\bigl((PQ)^{k}\\bigr)\\ge 0$.\n\\par (b) Prove that $PQ$ is diagonalizable over $\\mathbb{R}$ with every eigenvalue lying in $[0,1]$, and that its nonzero eigenvalues are exactly the squared cosines $\\cos^{2}\\theta_{1},\\dots,\\cos^{2}\\theta_{m}$ of the principal angles $\\theta_{i}\\in[0,\\tfrac{\\pi}{2}]$ between $\\mathcal{U}$ and $\\mathcal{V}$ (where $m=\\min(p,q)$), so that the whole sequence is a spectral ladder $\\operatorname{tr}\\bigl((PQ)^{k}\\bigr)=\\sum_{i=1}^{m}\\cos^{2k}\\theta_{i}$.\n\\par (c) Deduce the $k=1$ shadow $0\\le\\operatorname{tr}(PQ)\\le\\min(p,q)$, and as a concrete instance evaluate $\\operatorname{tr}(PQ)$ and $\\operatorname{tr}\\bigl((PQ)^{2}\\bigr)$ for $P=\\operatorname{diag}(1,1,0)$ and $Q=ww^{\\to p}$ with the unit vector $w=\\tfrac{1}{3}(2,1,2)^{\\to p}$ in $\\mathbb{R}^{3}$.",
    "answer": "\\[\\boxed{0\\le\\operatorname{tr}(PQ)\\le\\min(p,q);\\quad \\operatorname{tr}(PQ)=\\tfrac{5}{9},\\ \\operatorname{tr}\\bigl((PQ)^{2}\\bigr)=\\tfrac{25}{81}}\\]",
    "trap": "The lethal reflex is to declare $PQ$ symmetric. A strong student reasons: \"$P$ and $Q$ are symmetric, so $PQ$ is symmetric, hence its eigenvalues are real, and since $P,Q$ are projections $PQ$ is a projection too, so its eigenvalues are $0$ or $1$ and $\\operatorname{tr}(PQ)$ is just the integer rank of that product projection.\" Every link in this chain is false. The transpose of a product reverses order, $(PQ)^{\\to p}=Q^{\\to p}P^{\\to p}=QP$, so $PQ$ is symmetric ONLY in the degenerate commuting case $PQ=QP$; in general $PQ\\ne(PQ)^{\\to p}$. Already in $\\mathbb{R}^{2}$ with $P=\\bigl(\\begin{smallmatrix}1&0\\\\0&0\\end{smallmatrix}\\bigr)$ and $Q$ the projection onto the line at angle $\\tfrac{\\pi}{3}$, one gets $PQ=\\bigl(\\begin{smallmatrix}1/4&\\sqrt3/4\\\\0&0\\end{smallmatrix}\\bigr)$, which is not symmetric, is not idempotent, and has eigenvalue $\\tfrac14=\\cos^{2}\\tfrac{\\pi}{3}$ strictly between $0$ and $1$ — so $PQ$ is emphatically NOT a projection and $\\operatorname{tr}(PQ)$ is NOT an integer. In the part (c) instance the careless integer prediction gives $\\operatorname{tr}(PQ)\\in\\{0,1\\}$, whereas the true value is $\\tfrac59$. The reality and non-negativity of the trace are TRUE, but for a completely different reason than symmetry of $PQ$: they come from the cyclic law $\\operatorname{tr}\\bigl((PQ)^{k}\\bigr)=\\operatorname{tr}\\bigl((PQP)^{k}\\bigr)$ with $PQP$ symmetric positive semidefinite. Leaning on \"$PQ$ is symmetric\" reaches a partly-correct conclusion through a fully-wrong premise, and it actively misleads on the eigenvalues, on idempotency, and on the integrality of the trace.",
