          "Telescope the $(k+1)$-st commutator by inserting and removing $A^kBA$:\n$$A^{k+1}B-BA^{k+1}=\\big(A^{k+1}B-A^kBA\\big)+\\big(A^kBA-BA^{k+1}\\big)=A^k(AB-BA)+(A^kB-BA^k)A.$$",
          "Now substitute the two known relations: $AB-BA=A$ (hypothesis) into the first bracket and $A^kB-BA^k=kA^k$ (induction hypothesis) into the second:\n$$A^{k+1}B-BA^{k+1}=A^k\\cdot A+(kA^k)\\cdot A=A^{k+1}+kA^{k+1}=(k+1)A^{k+1},$$\ncompleting the induction.",
          "Take traces. Since $\\operatorname{tr}(A^kB)=\\operatorname{tr}(BA^k)$ always, the left side of $A^kB-BA^k=kA^k$ is traceless, so $k\\operatorname{tr}(A^k)=0$, i.e. $\\operatorname{tr}(A^k)=0$ for every $k\\ge1$. Equivalently the power sums $p_k=\\sum_i\\lambda_i^k$ of the eigenvalues vanish for $k=1,\\dots,n$.",
          "By Newton's identities the elementary symmetric functions satisfy $e_1=\\dots=e_n=0$, so $\\chi_A(x)=x^n$. Cayley–Hamilton then gives $A^n=0$, hence $A$ is nilpotent. $\\blacksquare$"
