          "From Step 4 of either method above, $\\operatorname{tr}(A^k)=0$ for $k=1,\\dots,n$. Writing $\\mu_1,\\dots,\\mu_r$ for the *distinct* nonzero eigenvalues with total multiplicities $c_j=\\sum_{\\lambda=\\mu_j}m_\\lambda>0$, these equations read $\\sum_{j=1}^r c_j\\,\\mu_j^k=0$ for $k=1,\\dots,r$.",
          "That is a Vandermonde system: the matrix $\\big(\\mu_j^k\\big)_{1\\le k,j\\le r}$ has determinant $\\big(\\prod_j\\mu_j\\big)\\prod_{i<j}(\\mu_j-\\mu_i)\\ne0$ since the $\\mu_j$ are nonzero and distinct. Hence $c_1=\\dots=c_r=0$, contradicting $c_j>0$ unless $r=0$.",
          "So $A$ has no nonzero eigenvalue: $\\chi_A(x)=x^n$, and Cayley–Hamilton gives $A^n=0$. (This also rules out any non-diagonalisable escape: the conclusion is read off the spectrum alone, independent of Jordan block structure.) $\\blacksquare$"
