          "Write each endpoint diagonal as $2=3-1$ and use multilinearity of the determinant in the first and last rows. Let $c_k=\\det C_k$ be the all-threes tridiagonal continuant ($k\\times k$, every diagonal $3$, off-diagonals $-1$). Splitting off the $-1$ correction at each end, and noting that deleting the first (resp. last) row and column of an all-threes block leaves an all-threes block of one smaller size, gives $d_n=c_n-2c_{n-1}+c_{n-2}$.",
          "The all-threes continuant satisfies $c_k=3c_{k-1}-c_{k-2}$ with $c_0=1,\\ c_1=3$; its characteristic roots are $\\tfrac{3\\pm\\sqrt5}{2}=\\varphi^{\\pm2}$ ($\\varphi=\\tfrac{1+\\sqrt5}{2}$), so by Binet $c_k=F_{2k+2}$ (check: $c_0=F_2=1,\\ c_1=F_4=3,\\ c_2=F_6=8$). Substitute: $d_n=F_{2n+2}-2F_{2n}+F_{2n-2}$. Using $F_{2n+2}=F_{2n+1}+F_{2n}$ and $F_{2n}=F_{2n-1}+F_{2n-2}$, this collapses to $d_n=F_{2n+1}-F_{2n}-F_{2n-1}+ (F_{2n}-F_{2n})\\cdots$; cleanly, $F_{2n+2}+F_{2n-2}=3F_{2n}$ (an instance of $F_{m+2}+F_{m-2}=3F_m$), so $d_n=3F_{2n}-2F_{2n}=F_{2n}$.",
