          "So $\\lambda_k=\\sum_{j=0}^{n-1}(x w^k)^j=\\dfrac{(xw^k)^n-1}{xw^k-1}=\\dfrac{x^n-1}{xw^k-1}$, using $w^{nk}=1$ (valid when $xw^k\\ne1$; when $xw^k=1$ the geometric sum is just $\\lambda_k=n$).",
          "Multiply over all $k$ with $xw^k\\ne1$: away from those collisions $\\det C_n=\\prod_{k=0}^{n-1}\\lambda_k=\\dfrac{(x^n-1)^n}{\\prod_{k=0}^{n-1}(xw^k-1)}$, an identity of rational functions in $x$ that we now evaluate and then extend to all $x$ by continuity.",
          "Evaluate the denominator using $\\prod_{k=0}^{n-1}(t-w^k)=t^n-1$. Setting $t=1/x$ and multiplying by $x^n$ gives $\\prod_{k=0}^{n-1}(1-xw^k)=1-x^n$, hence $\\prod_{k=0}^{n-1}(xw^k-1)=(-1)^n\\prod_{k=0}^{n-1}(1-xw^k)=(-1)^n(1-x^n)$.",
