          "**Rank.** If $x^n\\ne1$ all $\\lambda_k\\ne0$, so rank $=n$. If $x^n=1$, then $x^n-1=0$ forces $\\lambda_k=0$ for every $k$ with $xw^k\\ne1$. There is exactly one index $k_0$ with $xw^{k_0}=1$ (namely $w^{k_0}=x^{-1}$, which is an $n$-th root of unity precisely because $x^n=1$), and at that index $\\lambda_{k_0}=n\\ne0$. So exactly one eigenvalue survives: rank $=1$. This covers $x=1$ too (there $k_0=0$, $\\lambda_0=n$, and $C_n(1)$ is the all-ones matrix $J$, of rank $1$)."
