          "Use that $n$ is odd. Then $\\gcd(2,n)=1$, so $n\\mid 2j\\iff n\\mid j$; with $0\\le j\\le n$ the only solutions are $j=0$ (all clockwise) and $j=n$ (all counterclockwise). Each is a single word, so there are exactly $2$ closed walks of length $n$ from each fixed start. Summing over the $n$ start vertices, $W_n=2n$, and the walks counted are precisely the two oriented traversals of the whole cycle — the Hamiltonian loops. This is $\\boxed{W_n=2n}$, derived with no determinant at all.",
