    "remark": "Insight: every quantity the problem asks for is governed by one structural fact the Chebyshev identity quietly encodes — the eigenvalues of an odd cycle come in coincident pairs $k\\leftrightarrow n-k$, so $2(T_n(x/2)-1)=(x-2)\\,q(x)^2$ has a lone simple root at $x=2$ and a perfect-square tail. That single observation drives all three parts at once: the perfect square makes $\\det A=2$ (a $2$ times a square, never a generic integer), the double multiplicity is exactly the factor that survives in $\\operatorname{tr}(A^n)$ to give $W_n=2n$, and the same eigenvalues feed the AM-GM that pins $n\\ge 3$. The deepest lesson is the gap between an identity for $\\det(xI-A)$ and the spectrum with multiplicity: a degree-$n$ characteristic polynomial does not mean $n$ distinct eigenvalues, and on a symmetric circulant the periodic boundary forces $\\theta=\\tfrac{2\\pi k}{n}$ (not the path's $\\tfrac{\\pi k}{n}$, nor Chebyshev's extremum grid). The walk count is the combinatorial shadow of this: on an odd cycle the only way a $\\pm1$ walk returns to start in $n$ steps is to go all the way around, one of the two Hamiltonian orientations — which is why the hardest-looking spectral count secretly equals the simplest possible answer, $2n$."
