          "Compute $\\det(A-B)$. Here $A-B=t I+(S+S^{-1})-(R+R^{-1})=\\begin{pmatrix} t&0&0&2\\\\ 0&t&0&0\\\\ 0&0&t&0\\\\ 2&0&0&t\\end{pmatrix}$, because the inner cycle and skew-cycle edges cancel while the two wrap entries (positions $(1,4)$ and $(4,1)$) add to $2$. Permuting to group indices $\\{1,4\\}$ and $\\{2,3\\}$ block-diagonalises it: the $\\{1,4\\}$ block is $\\begin{pmatrix}t&2\\\\2&t\\end{pmatrix}$ with $\\det=t^2-4$, and the $\\{2,3\\}$ block is $t I_2$ with $\\det=t^2$. Thus $\\det(A-B)=t^{2}(t^{2}-4)$.",
          "Compute $\\det(A+B)$. Now $A+B=t I+(S+S^{-1})+(R+R^{-1})=\\begin{pmatrix} t&2&0&0\\\\ 2&t&2&0\\\\ 0&2&t&2\\\\ 0&0&2&t\\end{pmatrix}$: the inner edges double to $2$ and the wrap edges cancel, leaving a symmetric tridiagonal (path) matrix with off-diagonal $2$. Its determinant is the continuant $P_4(t)=t\\,P_3-4\\,P_2$ with $P_0=1,P_1=t,P_2=t^2-4,P_3=t^3-8t$, giving $P_4=t^4-12t^2+16=(t^2-2t-4)(t^2+2t-4)$. Hence $\\det(A+B)=t^{4}-12t^{2}+16$.",
          "Multiply: $\\det M(t)=t^{2}(t^{2}-4)\\,(t^{2}-2t-4)(t^{2}+2t-4)=t^{8}-16t^{6}+64t^{4}-64t^{2}$, which is (a). For (b), $M(t)$ is singular exactly when $\\det(A+B)=0$ or $\\det(A-B)=0$: from $t^2(t^2-4)=0$ we get $t\\in\\{0,2,-2\\}$ (a zero eigenvalue of $A-B$, whose spectrum is $t+\\{0,0,\\pm2\\}$); from $t^2-2t-4=0$ and $t^2+2t-4=0$ we get $t\\in\\{1\\pm\\sqrt5,\\,-1\\pm\\sqrt5\\}$ (a zero eigenvalue of $A+B$, whose spectrum is $t+\\{\\pm(1+\\sqrt5),\\pm(\\sqrt5-1)\\}$). These seven values are the only real singularities, each a coincidence inside one rotated combined lattice, never the naive $\\lambda_k=\\mp\\mu_k$.",
          "For (c), $\\det M(t)=t^2\\,(t^2-4)\\,(t^4-12t^2+16)$, even in $t$. With $s=t^2\\ge0$, the sign of $\\det M$ (away from $t=0$) is that of $(s-4)(s^2-12s+16)$, whose roots are $s=4$ and $s=6\\pm2\\sqrt5=(\\sqrt5\\pm1)^2$, ordered $6-2\\sqrt5<4<6+2\\sqrt5$. This cubic-in-$s$ is positive on $(6-2\\sqrt5,4)\\cup(6+2\\sqrt5,\\infty)$. Translating $s=t^2$: $\\det M(t)>0\\iff \\sqrt5-1<|t|<2\\ \\text{or}\\ |t|>1+\\sqrt5$. Headline: $\\boxed{\\det M(t)=t^{2}(t^{2}-4)(t^{2}-2t-4)(t^{2}+2t-4)}$."
