          "Read $A\\pm B$ off the graph directly. The circulant $S+S^{-1}$ is the adjacency of the $4$-cycle $1\\!-\\!2\\!-\\!3\\!-\\!4\\!-\\!1$; the skew part $R+R^{-1}$ is the same edge set with a sign on the wrap edges $(1,4),(4,1)$ (they carry $-1$ instead of $+1$), as the explicit $B$ shows. So in $A+B$ the two wrap edges are $1+(-1)=0$ and the two inner edges are $1+1=2$; in $A-B$ the wrap edges are $1-(-1)=2$ and the inner edges are $1-1=0$. The non-commuting blocks thus split into two completely different graphs.",
          "Hence $A+B=t I+2\\cdot(\\text{path }1\\!-\\!2\\!-\\!3\\!-\\!4)$ and $A-B=t I+2\\cdot(\\text{single edge }1\\!-\\!4)$. For $A-B$ the only coupling is the $\\{1,4\\}$ edge, so its eigenvalues are $t\\pm2$ (on $1\\!-\\!4$) and $t,t$ (isolated $2,3$): $\\det(A-B)=(t-2)(t+2)t^2=t^2(t^2-4)$. For $A+B$, the path $P_4$ with weight $2$ has eigenvalues $t+2\\cdot2\\cos\\tfrac{k\\pi}{5}$, $k=1,2,3,4$.",
          "Evaluate the path determinant with the Chebyshev factorisation $\\prod_{k=1}^{4}\\bigl(x-2\\cos\\tfrac{k\\pi}{5}\\bigr)=x^4-3x^2+1$. Setting the eigenvalues $t+4\\cos\\tfrac{k\\pi}{5}$ to zero means $-t/2=2\\cos\\tfrac{k\\pi}{5}$, so $\\det(A+B)=\\prod_k\\bigl(t+4\\cos\\tfrac{k\\pi}{5}\\bigr)=2^4\\prod_k\\bigl(\\tfrac t2-(-2\\cos\\tfrac{k\\pi}{5})\\bigr)=16\\bigl((t/2)^4-3(t/2)^2+1\\bigr)=t^4-12t^2+16$, since $\\{-2\\cos\\tfrac{k\\pi}{5}\\}=\\{2\\cos\\tfrac{k\\pi}{5}\\}$ as a set. The roots $t=\\pm2\\sqrt{\\tfrac{3\\pm\\sqrt5}{2}}=\\pm(1+\\sqrt5),\\pm(\\sqrt5-1)$ are the golden numbers — produced by a problem stated purely on roots of unity.",
