          "Symbol of $A-B$. From Method 1/2 its eigenvalues are $t\\pm2$ and $t$ (twice), so $\\det(A-B)=(t-2)(t+2)t^2=t^2(t^2-4)$. Symbol of $A+B$, the path matrix, has eigenvalues $t+4\\cos\\tfrac{k\\pi}{5}$; using $\\prod_{k=1}^{4}(x-2\\cos\\tfrac{k\\pi}{5})=x^4-3x^2+1$ with $x=t/2$ gives $\\det(A+B)=16\\bigl((t/2)^4-3(t/2)^2+1\\bigr)=t^4-12t^2+16$. Equivalently $t^4-12t^2+16=(t^2-6)^2-20=(t^2-6-2\\sqrt5)(t^2-6+2\\sqrt5)$, a biquadratic resultant of the circulant symbol against the rotated skew lattice.",
          "Hence $\\det M(t)=t^2(t^2-4)(t^4-12t^2+16)=t^{2}(t^{2}-4)(t^{2}-2t-4)(t^{2}+2t-4)$, giving (a). For (b): $M(t)$ singular $\\iff t^2(t^2-4)=0$ or $t^4-12t^2+16=0$. The first gives $t\\in\\{0,2,-2\\}$ — the circulant-flavoured branch $A-B$ losing rank; the biquadratic gives $t^2=6\\pm2\\sqrt5=(\\sqrt5\\pm1)^2$, so $t=\\pm(\\sqrt5+1),\\pm(\\sqrt5-1)$ — the path-flavoured branch $A+B$ losing rank. Exactly seven real singular values, none of them the naive shared-basis prediction $t=\\pm\\sqrt2,\\pm2\\pm\\sqrt2$.",
          "For (c), put $s=t^2\\ge0$: $\\det M=s(s-4)(s^2-12s+16)$, and since $s\\ge0$ its sign equals that of $(s-4)(s^2-12s+16)$, with $s$-roots $6-2\\sqrt5\\approx1.53$, $4$, $6+2\\sqrt5\\approx10.47$. This is positive on $(6-2\\sqrt5,4)\\cup(6+2\\sqrt5,\\infty)$, i.e. $\\det M(t)>0\\iff \\sqrt5-1<|t|<2$ or $|t|>1+\\sqrt5$. Spot checks: $t=1.6\\Rightarrow\\det M\\approx30>0$ (the inner band), $t=1\\Rightarrow-15<0$, $t=3\\Rightarrow-495<0$, $t=3.3\\Rightarrow294>0$ (the outer ray) — all consistent. $\\boxed{\\det M(t)=t^{2}(t^{2}-4)(t^{2}-2t-4)(t^{2}+2t-4)}$."
