    "remark": "Insight: this is the Matrix-Tree theorem wearing a Schur-complement disguise. The block $M=\\begin{pmatrix}A&B\\\\B&A\\end{pmatrix}$ is the grounded Laplacian of a $\\mathbb{Z}_2$ double cover, and its determinant factors as $\\det(A+B)\\det(A-B)$ — the spanning-tree counts of the two quotient graphs, the untwisted sheet ($A+B=I+L(K_3)$, a wheel with $\\tau=16$) and the sign-flipped sheet ($A-B$, with $\\tau=20$). The Schur complement is the same statement read electrically: eliminating one sheet is a Kron reduction that turns the cover into a weighted quotient whose reduced Laplacian determinant is again a tree count, so $\\det A\\cdot\\det(A-BA^{-1}B)$ rebuilds $\\tau(\\widetilde{\\Sigma})=320$. The trap is the heart of the problem: the scalar reflex $\\det M=\\det(A^2-B^2)$ silently assumes $AB=BA$ and returns $304$; the honest identity $\\det(A+B)\\det(A-B)=\\det(A^2-AB+BA-B^2)$ keeps the blocks in order and returns $320$. The non-commutativity is not a nuisance — it is precisely the sign twist that fuses two disconnected copies (which would give the spurious $256=16^2$) into a single connected cover. Eigenvalues, block diagonalisation, and Schur reduction all converge on the same integer, but only because each respects the order of the non-commuting, signed blocks."
