    "remark": "Insight: the prism's reduced Laplacian is not a scalar circulant but a BLOCK-circulant, and that single word changes the whole machine. A scalar circulant is diagonalised by one Fourier transform and its spectrum is read straight off the symbol $c(\\omega^k)$; a block-circulant is only block-diagonalised, leaving an honest $2\\times2$ symbol $M_k$ that must itself be diagonalised before any product can be taken. Here the rung is the off-diagonal of that symbol, and diagonalising it splits each Fourier mode into a symmetric branch $2-2\\cos\\theta_k$ (a bare cycle, carrying the mandatory zero mode) and an antisymmetric branch $4-2\\cos\\theta_k$ (a cycle shifted by $+2$). The product of quadratics over the roots of unity then collapses through $\\prod_{k}(x-2\\cos\\theta_k)=\\alpha^n+\\beta^n-2$ to a closed form governed by $z^2-4z+1$, whose roots $2\\pm\\sqrt3$ generate the Chebyshev / NSW recurrence $u_n=4u_{n-1}-u_{n-2}$ — emphatically not the Fibonacci-Lucas world of the wheel or fan, whose tridiagonal continuants live on $z^2-3z+1$ and the golden ratio. The trap dramatises the difference: pretend the layers decouple and you import the golden recurrence, lose the kernel, and produce non-integers. The correct reading factors the prism into two scalar circulants $L(C_n)$ and $L(C_n)+2I$, the $+2$ being the precise fingerprint of the rung, and the final count $\\tau(Y_n)=\\frac{n}{2}[(2+\\sqrt3)^n+(2-\\sqrt3)^n-2]=n(T_n(2)-1)$ is the cleanest possible signature that a block-circulant, not a circulant, was beating underneath."
